    <article id="conservation">
      <h2 class="conservation source_title">Conservation</h2>
      <p class="description">Conservation data measure information that is important for preservation and enhancement of protected areas and natural resources such as biodiversity.</p>

      <ul class="sources">
        <li id="conservation" data-slug="conservation" class="first">
          <div class="source_header">
            <strong>Global Protected Areas</strong>
            <i class="expand_arrow"></i>
          </div>

          <div class="source_body">
            <div class="source_download">
              <a href="http://www.protectedplanet.net" target="_blank" title="Download at project website">Download<i class="arrow_down"></i></a>
            </div>

            <div class="source_summary">
              <h3>Summary</h3>
              <p>All protected areas are from Protectedplanet.net which is the home of the World Database on Protected Areas (WDPA). The WDPA is a joint initiative between the IUCN and UNEP-WCMC to compile spatially referenced information about parks and protected areas globally. Data can be downloaded from <a href="http://www.protectedplanet.net/" target="_blank">Protected Planet site</a>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </li>

        <li id="biodiversity_hotspots" data-slug="biodiversity_hotspots" class="last">
          <div class="source_header">
            <strong>Biodiversity hotspots</strong>
            <i class="expand_arrow"></i>
          </div>

          <div class="source_body">
            <div class="source_download">
              <a href="#" class="disabled">Download<i class="arrow_down"></i></a>
            </div>

            <div class="source_summary">
              <h3>Summary</h3>
              <p>Biodiversity "hotspots" were first defined in 1988 by Norman Myers as areas characterized by high levels of endemic plants and habitat loss. Conservation International (CI) has since reevaluated and further defined the term. Under the CI definition, a region must "must contain at least 1,500 species of vascular plants as endemics, and it has to have lost at least 70 percent of its original habitat" to be considered a true biodiversity hotspot.</p>

              <p>Please note that the data visualization is a reproduction of CI's Biodiversity Hotspot shapefile.</p>
 
              <p class="credits">Credit: All text and images come from <a href="http://www.conservation.org/where/priority_areas/hotspots/Pages/hotspots_main.aspx.">http://www.conservation.org/where/priority_areas/hotspots/Pages/hotspots_main.aspx.</a> </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </article>

